Overview

Last week we covered 3 out of the 5 components of a graphic.

  • Data
  • Aesthetic mappings
  • Geometric objects

At the end of last week, we quickly introduced the fourth major component:

  • scales (legends and guides)

Iris data set

Take a look at the iris data set.

iris %>% glimpse()
## Rows: 150
## Columns: 5

The graphic starts with the data. The data are piped into the ggplot() function. The âparentâ ggplot() is usually where I map the x and y aesthetics. A scatter plot consists fundamentally of points therefore the geometric object used to display the data is the geom_point() function.

Make a scatter plot between Sepal.Length and Sepal.Width.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point()

We can examine the correlation between the two variables we plotted in the scatter plot. Correlation is a linear description. We can calculate the correlation matrix between variables in a data.frame using the cor() function.

iris %>% 
  select(Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width) %>% 
  cor()
##              Sepal.Length Sepal.Width
## Sepal.Length    1.0000000  -0.1175698
## Sepal.Width    -0.1175698   1.0000000

If the correlation coefficient depends on the level of Species we should expect to see a qualitatively different trend between the two variables across the groups in a scatter plot.

This is why we can use other aesthetics besides just position to visually represent information. One such aesthetic is color.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species))

Grouping

How can we group in R, or more specicially in the tidyverse? We use the group_by() function. To replicate what we did in Pandas we need to use group_by() and the group_map() function. First, letâs just see what the group_by() function does.

iris %>% 
  select(starts_with("Sepal."), Species) %>% 
  group_by(Species)
## # A tibble: 150 x 3
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##    Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Species
##           <dbl>       <dbl> <fct>  
##  1          5.1         3.5 setosa 
##  2          4.9         3   setosa 
##  3          4.7         3.2 setosa 
##  4          4.6         3.1 setosa 
##  5          5           3.6 setosa 
##  6          5.4         3.9 setosa 
##  7          4.6         3.4 setosa 
##  8          5           3.4 setosa 
##  9          4.4         2.9 setosa 
## 10          4.9         3.1 setosa 
## # ... with 140 more rows

The group_map() function will programmatically apply a function to each grouped data set.

iris %>% 
  select(starts_with("Sepal."), Species) %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  group_map( ~cor(.x) )
## [[1]]
##              Sepal.Length Sepal.Width
## Sepal.Length    1.0000000   0.7425467
## Sepal.Width     0.7425467   1.0000000
## 
## [[2]]
##              Sepal.Length Sepal.Width
## Sepal.Length    1.0000000   0.5259107
## Sepal.Width     0.5259107   1.0000000
## 
## [[3]]
##              Sepal.Length Sepal.Width
## Sepal.Length    1.0000000   0.4572278
## Sepal.Width     0.4572278   1.0000000

To combine everything into a data.frame we instead need to use the group_modify() function and include a data type conversion within our funtion to be applied.

iris %>% 
  select(starts_with("Sepal."), Species) %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  group_modify( ~as.data.frame( cor(.x) ) )
## # A tibble: 6 x 3
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##   Species    Sepal.Length Sepal.Width
##   <fct>             <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 setosa            1           0.743
## 2 setosa            0.743       1    
## 3 versicolor        1           0.526
## 4 versicolor        0.526       1    
## 5 virginica         1           0.457
## 6 virginica         0.457       1

I prefer the more tedious and explicit version within the tidyverse which requires us to using a mix of group_by(), ânestingâ, mutate, functional programming, and âunnestingâ.

We must group and then ânestâ the grouped subsetted dataframes within a larger or âouterâ data frame. We will use the tidyr::nest() function.

iris %>% 
  select(starts_with("Sepal."), Species) %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  tidyr::nest()
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##   Species    data                 
##   <fct>      <list>               
## 1 setosa     <tibble[,2] [50 x 2]>
## 2 versicolor <tibble[,2] [50 x 2]>
## 3 virginica  <tibble[,2] [50 x 2]>

We can âseeâ or interact with the grouped subsetted data by accessing the newly created data column in the nested dataframe. Letâs focus on the setosa group.

setosa_data <- iris %>% 
  select(starts_with("Sepal."), Species) %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  filter(Species == 'setosa')

Check the data type.

setosa_data %>% class()
## [1] "grouped_df" "tbl_df"     "tbl"        "data.frame"

We can access the data column with the $ operator.

setosa_data$data %>% class()
## [1] "list"

The grouped data frame contains lists!

setosa_data$data %>% length()
## [1] 1

We can access the elements in the list with the [[]] notation.

setosa_data$data[[1]] %>% class()
## [1] "tbl_df"     "tbl"        "data.frame"

Our grouped and nested data frame contains data frames!

setosa_data$data[[1]] %>% glimpse()
## Rows: 50
## Columns: 2
## $ Sepal.Length <dbl> 5.1, 4.9, 4.7, 4.6, 5.0, 5.4, 4.6, 5.0, 4.4, 4.9, 5.4, 4.~
## $ Sepal.Width  <dbl> 3.5, 3.0, 3.2, 3.1, 3.6, 3.9, 3.4, 3.4, 2.9, 3.1, 3.7, 3.~

We can then apply functions to the grouped data set.

setosa_data$data[[1]] %>% cor()
##              Sepal.Length Sepal.Width
## Sepal.Length    1.0000000   0.7425467
## Sepal.Width     0.7425467   1.0000000

To apply the correlation function, cor(), to all groups in the grouped data frame we need to use functional programming.

iris %>% 
  select(starts_with("Sepal."), Species) %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  mutate(cor_mat = purrr::map(data, cor))
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##   Species    data                  cor_mat          
##   <fct>      <list>                <list>           
## 1 setosa     <tibble[,2] [50 x 2]> <dbl[,2] [2 x 2]>
## 2 versicolor <tibble[,2] [50 x 2]> <dbl[,2] [2 x 2]>
## 3 virginica  <tibble[,2] [50 x 2]> <dbl[,2] [2 x 2]>

Convert from a matrix to a data frame.

iris %>% 
  select(starts_with("Sepal."), Species) %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  mutate(cor_mat = purrr::map(data, cor)) %>% 
  mutate(cor_df = purrr::map(cor_mat, as.data.frame))
## # A tibble: 3 x 4
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##   Species    data                  cor_mat           cor_df          
##   <fct>      <list>                <list>            <list>          
## 1 setosa     <tibble[,2] [50 x 2]> <dbl[,2] [2 x 2]> <df[,2] [2 x 2]>
## 2 versicolor <tibble[,2] [50 x 2]> <dbl[,2] [2 x 2]> <df[,2] [2 x 2]>
## 3 virginica  <tibble[,2] [50 x 2]> <dbl[,2] [2 x 2]> <df[,2] [2 x 2]>

Select and unnest â so convert from the nested object to a âregularâ data frame.

iris %>% 
  select(starts_with("Sepal."), Species) %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  mutate(cor_mat = purrr::map(data, cor)) %>% 
  mutate(cor_df = purrr::map(cor_mat, as.data.frame)) %>% 
  select(Species, cor_df) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest(cor_df)
## # A tibble: 6 x 3
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##   Species    Sepal.Length Sepal.Width
##   <fct>             <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 setosa            1           0.743
## 2 setosa            0.743       1    
## 3 versicolor        1           0.526
## 4 versicolor        0.526       1    
## 5 virginica         1           0.457
## 6 virginica         0.457       1

In R if you think what I did is too tedious, there is the corrr package from the tidymodels universe (which is related to tidyverse) dedicated to working with correlation matrices.

Themes and Colors

We saw that we could use the marker shape to also define or represent the group. Essentially means we are using the marker shape to denote a categorical variable.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species))

The scales_* family of functions allow us to control the behavior of the aesthetics represented on the geometric objects.

The default color for categorical or discrete colors is scale_color_discrete().

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete()

We can modify the legend title with the first argument to the scale function.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete("The color legend title")

If the scale legend titles are the same ggplot() will try to merge the scale legends together. The default categorical marker shape scale function is scale_shape_discrete().

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete("The Species value") +
  scale_shape_discrete("The Species value")

By default the legend is located on the right side of the graphic.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  scale_shape_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label")

We can move the legend position using the theme() function. Please see the theme() documentation for more info.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  scale_shape_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Or we can put the legend at the bottom.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  scale_shape_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

But there are some premade default theme âpatternsâ that we can apply. We saw the theme_classic() last week.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  scale_shape_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

The default theme pattern is âgreyâ.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  scale_shape_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  theme_grey() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

A dark theme.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  scale_shape_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  theme_dark() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

I prefer the black-white theme.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  scale_shape_discrete("A very long legend title for the Species value label") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

What if we needed to use lighter colors? How would the colors appear on the plot?

With the default discrete color scale, scale_color_discrete() we can lighten colors with the luminance or l argument.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete(l = 95) +
  scale_shape_discrete() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

We can further modify the color via the c argument or the chroma which controls the color intensity.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete(l = 95,c = 45) +
  scale_shape_discrete() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

If we need to use these kind of very light colors, we want to change to a dark background panel color.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete(l = 95,c = 45) +
  scale_shape_discrete() +
  theme_dark() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

I donât like the default discrete colors. Other color scales exist, some that much better suited for qualtiative or discrete variables. But some of those better scales are limited in the number of colors they can show. When I use the default discrete scale, I tend to make the markers darker because I prefer the white background.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_discrete(l = 45) +
  scale_shape_discrete() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

For categorical variable the ColorBrewer scales are quite good. The brewer color schemes are associated with the scale_color_brewer() function. Some useful color palettes to consider from Brewer are: Set1, Set2, Pastel1, Accent, and Dark2.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  scale_shape_discrete() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Examine other Brewer palettes.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Dark2") +
  scale_shape_discrete() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

The brewer documentation

The previous color palettes are not color blind safe. But thatâs where the ggthemes package helps out and we saw the colorblind friendly palette last week.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  ggthemes::scale_color_colorblind() +
  scale_shape_discrete() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Marker shape

A quick way to change the type of shape is to go from a SOLID to an OPEN shape. This is controlled by the default scale_shape_discrete() argument solid.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species)) +
  ggthemes::scale_color_colorblind() +
  scale_shape_discrete(solid = FALSE) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Letâs make the sizes bigger.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species),
             size = 4) +
  ggthemes::scale_color_colorblind() +
  scale_shape_discrete(solid = FALSE) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Compare with the solid shape.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species),
             size = 4) +
  ggthemes::scale_color_colorblind() +
  scale_shape_discrete(solid = TRUE) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

transparency

The marker transparency can help us âseeâ if there are multiple observations located at the same set of x and y aesthetic positions. The transparency is controlled by alpha. A value of alpha = 0.5 means that it takes 2 observations directly on top of each other to yield an opague marker.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species),
             size = 4,
             alpha = 0.5) +
  ggthemes::scale_color_colorblind() +
  scale_shape_discrete(solid = TRUE) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

If we use a very low value of alpha, such as alpha=0.1 we need 10 observations directly on top of each other to have a fully opague point.

  scale_shape_discrete(solid = TRUE) +

We can look up the various aesthetics associated with each type of geometric object.

Aesthetics specifications

Points with color and fill

The fill is associated with âfilling a region or area with colorâ. Think of painting a rectangle. The color aesthetic is associated with applying color to a point in space. ggplot2 says we use a âcolor strokeâ. Color is associated with points and lines, while fill is associated with polygons/regions/areas.
We can use points that have both color and fill if we want to use effectively 2 separate color scales. One for the point color stroke and one for the area region fill.

Use the marker fill, color, and shape to denote Species. So we are using three distinct aesthetics for one variable. To force the shapes with both fill and color, we will use the scale_shape_manual() function. Any of the scale_*_manual() functions give us the fine tune control to show exactly what we want. We specify the values as a named vector.

Use marker shapes 21, 24, and 25.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           fill = Species,
                           shape = Species),
             size = 6,
             alpha = 1.0) +
  ggthemes::scale_fill_colorblind() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c("setosa" = 21,
                                "versicolor" = 24,
                                "virginica" = 25)) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

We can control the âsizeâ of the color stroke with the stroke argument for points that have both fill and color.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           fill = Species,
                           shape = Species),
             size = 6,
             alpha = 1.0,
             stroke = 2.25) +
  ggthemes::scale_fill_colorblind() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c("setosa" = 21,
                                "versicolor" = 24,
                                "virginica" = 25)) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

We can apply a manual color scale if we would like. Hereâs a list of the names of colors we can type in.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           fill = Species,
                           shape = Species),
             size = 6,
             alpha = 1.0,
             stroke = 2.25) +
  ggthemes::scale_fill_colorblind() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("setosa" = 'gold',
                                'versicolor' = 'navyblue',
                                'virginica' = 'darkorange')) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c("setosa" = 21,
                                "versicolor" = 24,
                                "virginica" = 25)) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Facets

The last major component is the facet or subplot. Maybe we want to compare the relationship of variables across groups where the groups are represented by separate subplots. Itâs common to consider creating subplots with for-loops. We loop over an interating variable and that iterating variable controls how we subset the data to create the visual in each subplot.

Controlling the subplot based on a variable means there is a variable in the data set that dictages how we view the data. A facet is a âwindowâ is a particular view to a subset of the larger data set. The grammar of graphics considers facets (subplots) as an integral part of creating a visualization to graphically communicate relationships in our data.

In ggplot2, the facets are specifed by the facet_ family of functions outside of the geometric objects. Letâs include the Species as facets where the facets are âwrappedâ.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species),
             size = 4.5, alpha = 0.5) +
  facet_wrap( ~ Species ) +
  ggthemes::scale_color_colorblind() +
  scale_shape_discrete() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

In this case, since the marker shape and the marker color stroke also correspond to the facet variable, letâs turn off the legend.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Species,
                           shape = Species),
             size = 4.5, alpha = 0.5) +
  facet_wrap( ~ Species ) +
  ggthemes::scale_color_colorblind(guide = FALSE) +
  scale_shape_discrete(guide = FALSE) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Start to bring the Petal variables INTO the visualization of the Sepal variables. We have used color to denote a categorical variable, but color can also be used to represent a continuous variable! A continuous variable has a sequential order. We want to preserve that sequential order of the values. So the color scales for continuous variables are usually denoted as sequential. We can also have diverging scales, to represent a sequential order away from a central point (in two directions).

Letâs make a scatter plot between the Sepal variables with the Petal.Length represented by the color.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Petal.Length),
             size = 4.5) +
  theme_bw()

The default continuous color scale function is scale_color_continuous().

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Petal.Length),
             size = 4.5) +
  scale_color_continuous() +
  theme_bw()

I donât like the default color scale for continuous variables. I pretty much always switch to the viridis color palettes for sequential colors. The viridis color palette is controlled by the scale_*_viridis_c() for continuous colors.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = Petal.Length),
             size = 4.5) +
  scale_color_viridis_c() +
  theme_bw()

Sometimes we want to use a diverging color scale, if we are interested in the directioin away from a centrol or midpoint. We can create diviging color palettes with the scale_color_gradient2() function.

Sometimes it can be useful to âbinâ or represent the continuous variable categorically with discrete color bins. Create âbucketsâ or âbinsâ of constant color where the value âjumpsâ across the bins.

iris %>%

We can create the bins ourselves and have more control. For example we can convert a continuous variable into a categorical variable with the cut() function. We can create the categorical variable directly within the aes() function.

iris %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = cut(Petal.Length,
                                       breaks = quantile(Petal.Length,
                                                         c(0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1.0)),
                                       include.lowest = TRUE)),
             size = 4.5) +
  scale_color_viridis_d() +
  theme_bw()

If we apply the cut() function ourselves we probably want to modify the legend title.

iris %>%

                                       breaks = quantile(Petal.Length,

                                       include.lowest = TRUE)),
             size = 4.5) +

  theme_bw()

The simplest way to convert a continuous variable into a categorical variable is through binarizing. Just show two ordered values. This is easy to apply with conditional statements directly the aes() function.
For example, letâs compare Petal.Length to itâs median value.

iris %>%

  theme_bw()

Move the legend to the top.

iris %>%
